title: For Sale:  S&W 340PD .357 Magnum Centennial J-Frame Air-Lite Titanium / Scandium
postcontent: Centennial frame S&W, model 340PD, Scandium alloy frame with titanium 5-shot cylinder and stainless barrel liner.  Hogue contour grips, no-snag ramp sight, basic Uncle Mike's IWB holster.  Includes original box and keys for internal lock, as well as a cable lock and factory test cartridge.  Lots of bark, a bit of bite, and the lightest magnum-cartridge revolver you'll ever see.  This thing is so light and small in profile it's a dream for a CCW or a backup gun.  No external hammer, DA-only.  Certainly not an ideal range gun, but perfect for defensive carry.  Even if you miss, your target will be blind and deaf.  If you read the online reviews, you'll get the impression that this gun with full load 357 will make your hand bleed.  This is only true if you have never shot a round-butt J-Frame before and choke up high on the grip.  It's not nearly as bad to shoot as you might expect, but certainly not for a novice revolver shooter either.  Low round count - less than 50 rounds, mixed between .38 spl and .357 magnum.  Hate to part with it, but haven't been getting as many hours in at work, and the bills need paid.  As such cash is king, and trades will be of no interest.  Buyer must be 21+ and willing to sign an affidavit stating that there is no reason why they cannot legally purchase or possess a firearm.

title: For Sale:  FNH (Herstal) PBR Patrol Bolt Rifle .308 tactical rifle -VERY RARE-
location: East NC (near Farmville), Greenville, North Carolina
postcontent:
FN Herstal PBR in 308 caliber, with the 22" medium bull barrel.
In case you're not familiar, this rifle is based on the Pre-64 Winchester model 70 action, which is generally held by real shooters to be one of the finest rifle bolt actions ever made. It's rock-solid and designed to outlast me, you, and your kids. :)

Hogue fully overmolded stock with a solid aluminum bedding block/pillar system, free floating the barrel.

The scope is a cheap NCStar, but it's VERY high powered (10-40x!) and worked well the day I tried it out.

It includes a Harris-type bipod (not sure of brand, may be a Harris, not sure) and a really nice padded tactical (shock) sling.

The metal has been Duracoated in Flat Dark Earth (FDE) inside and out to protect from the elements, should you decide you need to shoot in foul weather.

This is an extremely rare rifle. There is exactly 1 like it for sale on gunbroker, and none that I can find on Armslist, if that tells you anything.

I've only had it to the range once (got it in trade a while back), but it shot just over 1 MOA with cheap steel case FMJ ammo at 200 yards in a nasty gusting crosswind. All the reviews and range reports I've found say that it's easily sub-MOA with decent ammo. I have no reason to doubt it.

The previous owner told me he had some bolt work done to it, so it's supposed to be slicker than stock. I don't have anything to compare it to, but the action is very smooth.

The trigger is adjustable. I'm not sure how it's set at the moment, but my "finger scale" says it feels like around 3.5 lbs with very little travel, so I'm happy.

I'm not really looking to trade, since that would defeat the purpose of "getting rid of a few guns", but you're welcome to offer if you have something you think I might like.

NIB CMMG GB AR-15

Caliber: 5.56x45mm NATO Chamber Barrel: 16" Bull Barrel, WASP Treated 4140 Chrome-Moly Steel, Hand Guard: M4 Hand Guard Sights/Gas Block: Piston System Stock: 6 Position Stock Trigger: Standard Trigger Magazine: 30rd PMAG (MAGPUL) 

W.A.S.P. Treated Barrel (Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating. 

Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.

postcontent:
THIS IS A PRE BAN GUN, AND MY FATHER WAS THE ONLY OWNER. HE BOUGHT IT AT A GUN SHOW IN 1981, WE FIRED A BOX OF 50 ROUNDS THROUGH IT, CLEANED IT AND DISPLAYED IT. UNTIL NOW, IT GOES UP FOR SALE OR TRADE.
 LIKE NEW CONDITION, WITH (4) 32 ROUND MAGS, FLASH SUPPRESSOR, FOREND PISTOL GRIP, FACTORY CUSTOM CASE, AND EVEN OWNERS MANUAL.
 KEEP IN MIND, DUE TO THIS BEING A PRE BAN GUN, THESE EXTRAS WERE ILLEGAL FOR THIS GUN AT ONE POINT, AND I AM PRETTY SURE IT WILL HAPPEN AGAIN IN THE VERY NEAR FUTURE, GET IT NOW AND YOU WILL BE GRANDFATHERED IN.
 PRICE $1,000.00 CASH OR TRADE ON AN H&K PISTOL
 CALL OR TEXT 865-660-8491 
HAVE PICTURES ON PHONE TO TEXT
 ALSO PLEASE KEEP IN MIND, WHEN YOU ARE SEARCHING FOR INFORMATION ON THIS WEAPON, IT IS NO LONGER PRODUCED, AND THIS IS THE ORGINAL MODEL, NOT ONE THAT WAS ALTERED BY THE COMPANY TO TRY AND MEET POST BAN ACCEPTANCE.

SINCE I HAVE HAD NUMEROUR QUESTIONS ABOUT THE “PRE-BAN” HERE IS A LITTLE INFORMATION I HOPE HELPS EVERYONE TO UNDERSTAND BETTER

The TEC-9 and, eventually, TEC-DC9 variants were listed among the 19 firearms banned by name in the USA by the now expired 1994 Federal Assault Weapons Ban (AWB).[1] This ban caused the cessation of their manufacture, and forced Intratec to introduce a newer model called the AB-10, a TEC-9 Mini without a threaded muzzle/barrel shroud and limited to a 10 round magazine instead of a 20 or 32 round magazine. However, it accepted the high capacity magazines of the pre-ban models.
 The Federal Assault Weapons Ban (AWB), or Public Safety and Recreational Firearms Use Protection Act, was a subtitle of the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994, a federal law in the United States that included a prohibition on the manufacture for civilian use of certain semi-automatic firearms, so called "assault weapons".[1] The 10-year ban was passed by Congress on September 13, 1994, and was signed into law by President Bill Clinton the same day. The ban only applied to weapons manufactured after the date of the ban's enactment.
 In the former U.S. law, the legal term assault weapon included certain specific semi-automatic firearm models by name (e.g., Colt AR-15, TEC-9, non-select-fire AK-47s produced by three manufacturers, and Uzis) and other semi-automatic firearms because they possess a minimum set of cosmetic features from the following list of features below:
 • Pistol Grip (Tec 9 has)
 • For end Grip (Tec9 has)
 • Flash Suppressor (Tec9 has)
 • Grenade Launcher (does not have)
 • Magazine that attached outside of the grip (Tec9 has)
 • Folding stock (does not have)
 • Bayonet Mount (does not have)
 During this ban, your weapon was legal with only 2(TWO) of the accessories. As you can see this PRE-BAN weapon has 4!!!!!

II. The Tec-9 Is A Semi-Automatic Version Of A Military Submachinegun

 The TEC-9 is a semi-automatic version of a military submachinegun. Although it has been marketed under various names -- the KG-9, the KG-99, the TEC-9, and the TEC-DC9 -- and by various companies owned and operated by the Garcia family, the basic design of the weapon has remained virtually unchanged. The company decided to manufacture the KG-9 because of the growing market for military style guns in the United States. The KG-9's manual described it as: 
Combining the high capacity and controlled firepower of the military submachinegun with the legal status and light weight of a handgun.The term "assault pistol" was coined by the firearms industry to describe the KG-9 was an illegal machine gun, due to the ease with which it could be converted to fully automatic fire.


A. The KG-9 Was Banned as a Machine Gun, and Renamed the KG-99

 In 1982, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms ruled that the KG-9 was an illegal machine gun, due to the ease with which it could be converted to fully automatic fire.

 The company redesigned the KG-9's bolt to make conversion more difficult, and renamed the weapon the KG-99. Otherwise, the design remained essentially unchanged. Intratec confirmed that like its predecessor, the KG-99 could be fairly described as "combining the high capacity and controlled firepower of the military submachinegun with the legal status and light weight of a handgun."

 Intratec U.S.A. ("Intratec") manufactured a vertical foregrip for use with the KG-99, which it marketed as an "Assault Grip." Intratec used the term "Assault Grip" in marketing the foregrip, "[b]ecause you basically hold the gun with two hands like you would as assault weapon, a military weapon."

 In November 1982, and again in March 1985, the ATF notified Intratec that it was unlawful to possess a KG-99 and an attachable foregrip, even though the pistol and the foregrip were disassembled. Although Intratec understood that they should not be selling the assault grip, he continued to sell it as an accessory for the KG-99, stamping on the order form that "ATF has ruled that the KG-250 assault grip may not be attached legally to the KG-99 or the old model KG-9."

 B. Intratec Rename the KG-99 the TEC-9, and Continued to Sell the "Assault Grip."

 Intratec renamed the KG-99 the TEC in August 1985. The TEC-9 was substantially identical to the KG-99, with just a few cosmetic changes. The company resumed marketing the assault grip without any warning, advertising that it "Attaches to All TEC-9" Intratec advertised the TEC-9 as a "High-spirited" weapon that is "as tough as your toughest customer." The company’s brochure emphasized the weapon’s "paramilitary" appeal, its "Military blowback design," and its "Combat-type" sights. The brochure depicted a smoking target of a human being shot dozens of times through the head and the heart in what appears to be a fusillade of automatic weapons fire. In April 1987, Intratec was sued by the Estate of David Bengston in Connecticut state court. The complaint alleged that the decedent, a school custodian, was fatally shot in the head with a TEC-9M ["Mini"], and that Intratec "knew or should have known that the TEC-9M gun was and is primarily suited for an/or used in criminal activity," and that it "lacks legitimate use, such as sporting, law enforcement of self-protection." In November 1987, Carlos Garcia formed Navegar in order to take the assets of the business back from his father and avoid Intratec’s liabilities. Navegar continued to manufacture and market the TEC-9, and continued to do business as Intratec. Intratec U.S.A. declared bankruptcy in 1989, with the Bengston and Alicki lawsuits as its only significant liabilities.

If any of you guys have been watching the news lately, you are probably aware that in the next few weeks the senate plans to vote on a bill called ( S. 649) the "safe communities, safe schools " act.
Well, the news and the government are making it sound like it's only going to affect the background checks. 
But what they're NOT telling people is that Schumer and Feinstein have add or "dog eared " an amendment to that law that if the background check law is passed, it will also ban "certain rifles" and "certain magazines". 
I got a e-mail from the NRA the other day stating this. It's in their grassroots alert Vol 20 15 04/12/2013 .
Now I didn't really believe it too much until this morning when I got an email from my Senator Lindsey Graham this morning stating pretty much the same thing.
People , the news has fooled many into thinking the assault ban has been defeated. 
If you look back to the 1990's they did the same thing with Bill Clinton. The old assault weapons bans was "defeated" and then they just passed it by tagging or "dog earing" it to a different law. 
I'm not selling anything to make a profit off of this information... I just want to spread what I've heard and read. 
Check it out for yourself..... But you have to dig deep to find the truth.
Check out the NRA's grassroots alert website or contact senator Lindsey Graham's office and ask to be put on their email list.

title: For Sale:  Firearms Customization Service
postcontent:
Tired of having a dirty gun that sticks and jams every chance it gets?  How about a gun with the same old plain wood or wood substitute stock with a blued barrel at the range?  Ever considered turning your standard hunting gun from looking like a sore thumb in the woods to a camouflaged weapons system? How about showing off your pride for your favorite sports team? Or cleaning up that rusty old shotgun that has sat up in the attic for the past three decades?

Well, you have found the right place…I take ordinary guns and turn them into custom finished firearms.  I have helped many friends and family members take guns that have sat in their attics or garage, neglected for years and turn them into restored, respectable firearms.  If you would like your duck gun camouflaged, a sport rifle to show off you team’s colors or just restore Dad’s old gun…I can take care of all of them in house.  I start by meeting with you and deciding what you would like to see when the project is finished and discuss the possible options to get the desired results.  Once we have a plan, I go to work and get the firearms back into shape, taking pictures to send to you as updates along the way so you can see the progression of your firearm’s refinishing.  When it is all said and done, we meet back up again for you to inspect the firearm and give it the final approval.
If you would like a new stock, I can give you a number of options including synthetic, traditional wood or wood laminate as well as choice of coloring.
If you would like to have your gun colored I use Duracoat finishes, which provide one of, if not the best and most durable finishes available for a firearm.  Once cured for the appropriate time, the gun becomes VERY difficult to scratch or rust and is very difficult to remove.
The typical process goes something like this:
Disassembly
Removal of rust or other foreign matter
Deep, thorough cleaning of all parts
 Apply any new coatings or colorings that are to be done
Second cleaning
Oiling/greasing of critical parts
Reassembly
Final cleaning and touch ups

Prices vary depending on services to be performed.  The pictures are of firearms I have done for outside clients to their specifications…I have not yet had a single complaint or request for re-work to be performed.  All work is guaranteed to function per manufacturer’s specifications.  I truly enjoy doing this type of work and am very meticulous in my procedures, if there is anything you are unhappy with once your firearm is complete, simply let me know and I will remedy the situation immediately. 

Attached are pictures of a standard Ruger 10/22 that I customized for an Ohio State fan.  Unfortunately I can upload only three pictures per listing, if you would like to see other examples of my work, please shoot me and email and I will be happy to send some to you.  Thanks. 

For all of the non-Buckeye fans out there, those are not marijuana leaves...they are BUCKEYE leaves.
